he little–researched poetry of Gregory of Nazianzus reflects a remarkable interweaving of Judeo–Christian thought and the Greek–Pagan poetic tradition. This book includes a bilingual edition and analysis of the imagery in the double–poem “On Silence During Lent” (Carm. II,1,34A/B), a work that offers an especially vivid illustration of the often innovative interposition of different traditions.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAsceticism -- Poetry. 0aAsceticismvPoetry. 0aGregory, -- of Nazianzus, Saint -- Criticism and interpretation. 0aGregory, -- of Nazianzus, Saint. -- Carmina de se ipso. 0aGregory, -- of Nazianzus, Saint. -- Poems. -- Selections. 0aSilence in literature. 4aBildersprache. 4aChristliche Dichtung. 4aGregor von Nazianz. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aChristian poetry.  aGregory of Nazianzus.  aimagery.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Classics and Near East Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110636178oZDB-23-GCN08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2014z9783110369618oZDB-23-DGD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG0 cEPUBz97831103697240 cprintz978311034550640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311034586540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110345865423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110345865/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGDb2014  aZDB-23-DGGb2014  aZDB-23-GCNc2000d2014